Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 7a1dbc4803bf78bfc0c574e6676b3c5def4cdae3
Overall this is shaping up to be a productive change.  I haven't reviewed the full patchset, because there are some systemic patterns we need to go through and fix, but overall, I'm in support.
Please don't use a default parameter here.  Fill in the parameter where it's needed.

Please don't use inline lambdas like this, and especially don't convert an existing call to using inline lambdas.  Either leave it the way it is as an rvalue, or move it over to the new pattern of a normal method.
The old one was better.  Why did this change?

> The old one was better.  Why did this change?

Done. But we should remove `const`
"Why did this change?" was not answered.

> "Why did this change?" was not answered.

The reason is that the previous getSubTree method does not accept the const type
```
std::span<const std::string> interfaces
```
This is now fixed with the string_view change.
If we're changing this, we should be moving to std::span<const std::string_view>.

> If we're changing this, we should be moving to std::span<const std::string_view>.

Ack.
we should be moving to std::span<const char*> instead of std::span<const std::string_view>, because the async_method_call method does not accept parameters of type string_view
Same as above.  Please don't move to lvalue lambdas.
Overall I'm in support of this change, but we need to get a couple of the refactoring things understood around why some things changed const-ness, and why std::vector was used so heavily.

> Why was this removed?

Because std::span does not accept std::array of const type

```
../redfish-core/lib/processor.hpp:1225:13: error: could not convert ‘redfish::processorInterfaces’ from ‘const std::array<const char*, 2>’ to ‘std::span<const char*>’
 1225 |             processorInterfaces);
      |             ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
      |             |
      |             const std::array<const char*, 2>
```
Looks like you were missing a const in front of std::span.

> Looks like you were missing a const in front of std::span.

span does not propagate const

```
Propagating const for a type like *span* doesn't actually make much sense, since it cannot protect you from anything anyway.
```

But we can fix it like this:
std::span<const char* const>
Same here.  The old code was correct.
This moving is a little odd, but I guess that's ok.
array please.  Please fix all of these.
Can you comment why these needed to move from lvalue lambdas to inline rvalues.  It's not clear to me why that would be necessary in this refactor.

> Can you comment why these needed to move from lvalue lambdas to inline rvalues.  It's not clear to me why that would be necessary in this refactor.

Because you said:
```
Please don't use inline lambdas like this, and especially don't convert an existing call to using inline lambdas.  Either leave it the way it is as an rvalue, or move it over to the new pattern of a normal method.
```
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/59428/2..5/include/openbmc_dbus_rest.hpp#b1645
Please make an API that can accept all the callables we need, or, if you want to refactor, stack refactoring patches ahead of this one.

> Please make an API that can accept all the callables we need, or, if you want to refactor, stack refactoring patches ahead of this one.

I want to refactor in a later commit, currently I don't want to break this commit, and hope to merge as soon as possible, so here I choose to fallback

> I want to refactor in a later commit

Then refactor in a later commit.  This commit has incremental refactoring of changing lambdas/inline methods that either doesn't need to be done, or needs to be done in a separate commit.

>hope to merge as soon as possible

Great.  Get the patchsets broken up appropriately, and following the coding standards, and they can merge.  I don't see anything fundamental that would hold this up, but it needs to not change to patterns that we're trying to deprecate (ie lvalue lambdas)
Why do we need an intermediate here?  processorInterfaces is a std::array that the helper function should be able to use directly.
You don't need double const here.

> You don't need double const here.

No, Since std::span does not accept const, and we need to pass in const, it can only be std::span<const char* const>
The latest patchsets were just including what you use.
